In src/fieldtrial/inference/orchestration.py, derive a null value from the framework and thread it into every inference call alongside _alternative_from_framework. Add:

def _null_value_from_framework(spec: Any, metric: Any) -> float:
    tf = getattr(spec, "test_framework", None)
    if tf is None:
        return 0.0
    kind = str(getattr(tf, "kind", "two_sided"))
    margins = getattr(tf, "margins", None) or {}
    raw = margins.get(str(metric), getattr(tf, "default_margin", 0.0))
    margin = abs(float(raw or 0.0))
    if kind == "non_inferiority":
        return -margin  # H0: effect <= -margin vs H1: effect > -margin
    if kind == "inferiority":
        return margin   # H0: effect >= margin vs H1: effect < margin (alternative='less')
    return 0.0

Then pass null_value=_null_value_from_framework(spec, metric) in _run_randomization_inference (randomization_test call, line ~552), _run_market_bootstrap (bootstrap_inference, ~594), _run_jackknife (jackknife_inference, ~614), _run_conformal (both conformal calls, ~643/653 — these already accept null_value), and _run_few_cluster_wild_bootstrap; replace the hardcoded null_value=0.0 at line ~843 with the framework-derived value. Two required accompaniments: (1) scale consistency — TestFrameworkSpec.effect_scale defaults to 'relative_lift' while these statistics operate on the estimate/effect scale, so either convert the margin to the estimate scale (margin * baseline) before shifting the null, or emit a warning and skip the shift when effect_scale=='relative_lift' cannot be converted; (2) add a regression test: neutral market effects with kind='non_inferiority', default_margin large relative to noise, assert p_value < alpha (and assert equality with the kind='superiority' p-value fails, i.e., the two frameworks now diverge).

In src/fieldtrial/power/simulation.py, make the not-achievable case explicit instead of falling back to the largest grid lift:

def estimate_mde_from_simulations(
    curve: list[PowerCurvePoint],
    *,
    target_power: float = 0.8,
) -> float:
    """Return the smallest simulated lift whose power meets target_power.

    Returns float("inf") when no lift on the simulated grid reaches the
    target power (i.e. the MDE is not achievable on this grid).
    """
    for point in sorted(curve, key=lambda item: item.lift):
        if point.power >= target_power:
            return point.lift
    return float("inf")

(Alternatively raise ValueError("target power not reached on simulated lift grid") if callers should be forced to widen the grid.) Add a unit test in tests/unit/test_power.py asserting that a curve whose max power is below target_power yields inf (or raises), and that an empty curve behaves the same.

